<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <%- include('partials/head') %>
</head>
<body>

<%- include('partials/header') %>

<main>

  <!-- ── Page hero ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="hero hero--island" style="padding: 3.5rem 0;">
    <div class="hero__image-slot" aria-hidden="true"></div>
    <div class="container">
      <div class="hero__content">
        <span class="hero__eyebrow">McNutt's Island, Nova Scotia</span>
        <h1>The Island</h1>
        <p class="hero__description">
          Ten thousand years of continuous human presence. Mi'kmaq homeland,
          Black Loyalist settlement, lighthouse, WWII battery, and lobster fishery.
          This is the full story of a small island with a long memory.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <%- include('partials/svg/divider-treeline') %>

  <!-- ── Mi'kmaq History ───────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="editorial">
        <div>
          <span class="section__eyebrow">Ten Thousand Years</span>
          <h2>Mi'kmaq Homeland</h2>
          <p>
            Long before European contact, Mi'kmaq people inhabited and traveled through
            the territory surrounding Shelburne Harbour, which they called Ounemegeek — a name
            for the shelter the deep harbour provided. The island and its surrounding waters
            were part of Mi'kma'ki, the ancestral and unceded territory of the Mi'kmaq Nation.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Mi'kmaq maintained seasonal camps, fished the abundant harbour, and moved
            through a landscape they had known for millennia. The Sipekne'katik First Nation,
            whose traditional territory includes this region, maintains a living connection to
            these lands and waters.
          </p>
          <p>
            McNutt's Island Alliance acknowledges this history and seeks to engage in genuine
            partnership with Mi'kmaq communities on questions of stewardship and the island's
            future — including the question of the island's name.
          </p>
          <a href="/naming" class="btn btn--outline-dark mt-3">The Naming Conversation</a>
        </div>
        <div class="illustration-slot">
          <%- include('partials/svg/illus-canoe') %>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <%- include('partials/svg/divider-shore') %>

  <!-- ── Black Loyalist ────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="section section--alt">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="editorial editorial--reverse">
        <div>
          <span class="section__eyebrow">1783 &ndash; The Black Loyalists</span>
          <h2>Promised Land, Broken Promises</h2>
          <p>
            In 1783, following the American Revolutionary War, Black Loyalists — free Black
            people who had sided with the British in exchange for promises of freedom and land —
            arrived on Nova Scotia's South Shore. Nearby Birchtown became the largest free Black
            settlement in North American history at the time, with more than 3,000 residents.
          </p>
          <p>
            Many of these settlers had connections to McNutt's Island and Shelburne Harbour.
            The promises made to them were largely broken: land grants were smaller than promised,
            the land itself often poor, and discrimination rampant. Within a decade, many had
            left for Sierra Leone aboard the "Province of Freedom" ships.
          </p>
          <p>
            This history — one of the most significant and underrecognized chapters in both
            Canadian and African-American history — is woven into the fabric of McNutt's Island.
            The Black Loyalist Heritage Society in Shelburne preserves and continues this story.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="editorial__image img-placeholder" style="min-height: 320px;">
          <span class="img-placeholder__icon" aria-hidden="true">&#9875;</span>
          <span class="img-placeholder__label">Historical photograph</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <%- include('partials/svg/divider-wave') %>

  <!-- ── Lighthouse ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="editorial">
        <div>
          <span class="section__eyebrow">Since 1788</span>
          <h2>The Lighthouse</h2>
          <p>
            The McNutt's Island lighthouse has guided vessels into Shelburne Harbour since 1788,
            making it one of the oldest lighthouses in Canada. Built originally of wood, the current
            octagonal wooden tower dates to 1833. It stands 21 metres tall on the island's
            southwestern headland, visible for miles in clear conditions.
          </p>
          <p>
            The lighthouse was decommissioned in the 1980s and is now managed by the
            McNutt's Island Lighthouse Preservation Society. Restoration work has been ongoing,
            and the lighthouse is accessible to visitors who make the crossing from Gunning Cove.
          </p>
          <p>
            The lighthouse keeper's dwelling and fog alarm building still stand nearby, offering
            a glimpse into the life of those who maintained this critical navigational aid through
            Nova Scotia's often brutal winter storms.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="illustration-slot">
          <%- include('partials/svg/illus-lighthouse') %>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <%- include('partials/svg/divider-shore') %>

  <!-- ── WWII Battery ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="section section--alt">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="editorial editorial--reverse">
        <div>
          <span class="section__eyebrow">1939 &ndash; 1945</span>
          <h2>The WWII Gun Battery</h2>
          <p>
            During the Second World War, McNutt's Island was fortified as part of Canada's
            coastal defence network. A gun battery was installed at McNutt's Head to protect
            Shelburne Harbour — a strategic deep-water port used as a convoy assembly point
            for trans-Atlantic crossings.
          </p>
          <p>
            The concrete battery emplacements remain visible today, partially reclaimed by
            the forest. The battery was armed with two six-inch naval guns capable of engaging
            surface vessels at considerable range. Supporting infrastructure included barracks,
            searchlight positions, and communications equipment.
          </p>
          <p>
            The wartime period brought significant activity and population to the island —
            a striking contrast to its usual quiet, and a reminder that even remote places
            are not immune to the currents of world events.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="illustration-slot">
          <%- include('partials/svg/illus-bunker') %>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <%- include('partials/svg/divider-birds') %>

  <!-- ── Lobster Fishery ───────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="editorial">
        <div>
          <span class="section__eyebrow">The Working Island</span>
          <h2>The Lobster Fishery</h2>
          <p>
            McNutt's Island sits at the edge of some of the most productive lobster grounds
            on Nova Scotia's South Shore. The lobster fishery has been the economic backbone
            of the surrounding communities for generations — and it remains so today.
          </p>
          <p>
            Fishing families maintain seasonal camps on the island, returning each spring for
            the lobster season. This working connection to the island is one of its most vital
            threads — a living relationship between people and place that has persisted through
            all the historical changes around it.
          </p>
          <p>
            The health of the lobster fishery is tied to the health of the marine ecosystem:
            the eelgrass beds, the intertidal zones, the water quality of Shelburne Harbour.
            Environmental stewardship and the fishery are not in opposition — they depend on
            each other.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="illustration-slot">
          <%- include('partials/svg/illus-lobster-boat') %>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── CTA ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="section section--dark">
    <div class="container container--narrow text-center">
      <h2>This Island Is Worth Caring About</h2>
      <p style="color:var(--sand); max-width:520px; margin: 1rem auto 2rem;">
        Join the McNutt's Island Alliance and become part of the community working to
        understand, celebrate, and protect this place.
      </p>
      <div style="display:flex; gap:1rem; justify-content:center; flex-wrap:wrap;">
        <a href="/community" class="btn btn--primary">Join the Alliance</a>
        <a href="/naming"    class="btn btn--outline">The Naming Conversation</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</main>

<%- include('partials/footer') %>
<script src="/js/main.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
